one of the following viruses is the causative agent?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cytomegalovirus","Epstein-Barr","Hepatitis B","Herpes simplex","Varicella zoster"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHairy leukoplakia is caused by \u003Cstrong\u003EEpstein-Barr virus\u003C/strong\u003E infection. While \u003Cstrong\u003Eherpes simplex virus\u003C/strong\u003E can cause oral ulcers, it does not cause hairy leukoplakia. \u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B virus\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects the liver and does not cause oral lesions. \u003Cstrong\u003EVaricella zoster virus\u003C/strong\u003E causes chickenpox and shingles but not oral hairy leukoplakia. \u003Cstrong\u003ECytomegalovirus\u003C/strong\u003E can cause oral ulcers in immunocompromised patients but is not associated with hairy leukoplakia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe condition typically presents as white, corrugated patches on the tongue, usually on the lateral borders. It cannot be scraped off. It is most commonly seen in immunocompromised patients, particularly those with HIV infection, but can occur in other immunocompromised states such as organ transplant recipients or patients on long-term immunosuppression.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oral hairy leukoplakia is caused by Epstein-Barr virus infection and is commonly seen in immunocompromised patients, particularly those with HIV.","Hairy leukoplakia presents as white patches on the tongue that cannot be scraped off."],"references":["Rathee M, Jain P. Hairy Leukoplakia. [Updated 2023 Apr 10]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554591/","Greenspan JS, Greenspan D, Webster-Cyriaque J. Hairy leukoplakia; lessons learned: 30-plus years. Oral Dis. 2016 Apr;22 Suppl 1:120-7. doi: 10.1111/odi.12393. PMID: 27109280.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51374"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15169"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21254"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21254"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/EJd7XXy40VIk97SKS4WuEoPxJQmtzQ.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/EJd7XXy40VIk97SKS4WuEoPxJQmtzQ.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":385,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51374"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-27T16:31:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T16:31:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7860"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65928"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember